  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>Every DCF model has limitations. Here are factors that could skew our intrinsic value estimate for TJX.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>International expansion:</strong> The model assumes steady state growth, but if TJX dramatically accelerates its footprint in Europe and Australia, revenue growth could persistently exceed our 9% estimate.</li>
    <li><strong>Share buybacks:</strong> TJX regularly buys back stock. Fewer outstanding shares over the next 5-10 years will mechanically increase the intrinsic value per share.</li>
    <li><strong>Inventory glut opportunities:</strong> Macroeconomic shocks that leave traditional retailers with excess inventory allow off-price retailers like TJX to acquire premium merchandise at steep discounts, potentially spiking margins.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Margin mean reversion:</strong> At ~12%, TJX's operating margins are near historic highs. If wage inflation, freight costs, or intensified competition force markdowns, margins could compress.</li>
    <li><strong>E-commerce threat:</strong> While off-price is uniquely resistant to e-commerce, a massive shift toward digital discount models (like Shein or Temu moving upscale) could eventually erode physical store traffic.</li>
    <li><strong>Economic recession:</strong> TJX is resilient during downturns, but a severe and prolonged recession could still impair consumer spending overall, dampening top-line growth.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use DCF instead of a P/E multiple for retail?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">While P/E multiples are common, they are relative and subject to market sentiment swings. A DCF grounds the valuation strictly in the cash the business generates. For a mature, cash-cow retailer like TJX, cash generation is the ultimate arbiter of value.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why an 8.5% discount rate?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">The 10-year Treasury yields around 4.18%. Adding a standard equity risk premium of ~5% and factoring in TJX's relatively low risk profile (it's a defensive retailer), an 8.5% rate reflects a fair required return for this specific company.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is TJX overvalued?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">According to our base case DCF model, the market price reflects an optimistic growth scenario that exceeds our 9% base case projection. However, the verdict text updates dynamically based on the numbers—check the top of the page for the exact gap between price and value.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>How often is this updated?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">This analysis is updated periodically when The TJX Companies releases new annual reports or material financial data.</div>
    </details>
